# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battle-of-sinop
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The era featured mass-conscripted armies, rapid transportation (first on railroads, then by sea and air), telegraph and wireless communications, and the concept of total war.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In terms of technology, this era saw the rise of rifled breech-loading infantry weapons capable of high rates of fire, high-velocity breech-loading artillery, chemical weapons, armoured warfare, metal warships, submarines, and aircraft.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] One of the main features of industrial warfare is the concept of "total war".
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The term was coined during World War I by Erich Ludendorff (and again in his 1935 book *Total War*), which called for the complete mobilization and subordination of all resources, including policy and social systems, to the German war effort.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] It has also come to mean waging warfare with absolute ruthlessness, and its most identifiable legacy today has been the reintroduction of civilians and civilian infrastructure as targets in destroying the enemy's ability to engage in war.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] There are several reasons for the rise of total warfare in the 19th century.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] As countries' capital and natural resources grew, it became clear that some forms of warfare demanded more resources than others.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Consequently, the greater cost of warfare became evident.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] An industrialized nation could distinguish and then choose the intensity of warfare that it wished to engage in.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Additionally, warfare was becoming more mechanized and required greater infrastructure.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Combatants could no longer live off the land, but required an extensive support network of people behind the lines to keep them fed and armed.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] This required the mobilization of the home front.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Modern concepts like propaganda were first used to boost production and maintain morale, while rationing took place to provide more war material.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The earliest modern example of total war was the American Civil War.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Grant and William Tecumseh Sherman were convinced that, if the North was to be victorious, the Confederacy's strategic, economic, and psychological ability to wage war had to be definitively crushed.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] They believed that to break the backbone of the South, the North had to employ scorched earth tactics, or as Sherman called it, "Hard War".
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Sherman's advance through Georgia and the Carolinas was characterized by the widespread destruction of civilian supplies and infrastructure.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In contrast to later conflicts, the damage done by Sherman was almost entirely limited to property destruction.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In Georgia alone, Sherman claimed he and his men had caused $100,000,000 in damages.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Conscription is the compulsory enrollment of civilians into military service.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Conscription allowed the French Republic to form *La Grande Armée*, what Napoleon Bonaparte called "the nation in arms", which successfully battled smaller, professional European armies.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Conscription, particularly when the conscripts are being sent to foreign wars that do not directly affect the security of the nation, has historically been highly politically contentious in democracies.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] For instance, during World War I, bitter political disputes broke out in Canada (see Conscription Crisis of 1917), Newfoundland, Australia and New Zealand (see Compulsory Military Training) over conscription.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Canada also had a political dispute over conscription during World War II (see Conscription Crisis of 1944).
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Both South Africa and Australia put limits on where conscripts could fight in WWII.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Similarly, mass protests against conscription to fight the Vietnam War occurred in several countries in the late 1960s.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Russia, as well as many smaller nations such as Switzerland, retain mainly conscript armies.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Prior to the invention of the motorized transport, combatants were transported by wagons, horses and by marching.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] With the advent of locomotives, large groups of combatants, supplies, and equipment were able to be transported faster and in larger numbers.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] To counter this, an opposing force would destroy rail lines to hinder their enemies' movements.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] General Sherman's men during the American Civil War, would destroy tracks, heat the rails, and wrap them around trees.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The mass transportation of combatants was further revolutionized with the advent of the internal combustion engine and the automobile.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Combined with the widespread use of the machine gun, the horse, after millennia of use, was finally supplanted in its war time role.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] During both WWI and WWII, trucks were used to carry combatants and materiel, while cars and jeeps were used to scout enemy positions.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The mechanization of infantry occurred during WWII.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The tank, a product of World War I independently invented by the British and French to break through trenches while withstanding machine gun fire, while discounted by many, came into its own.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Tanks evolved from thin-skinned, lumbering vehicles into fast, powerful war machines of various types that dominated the battlefield and allowed the Germans to conquer most of Europe.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] As a result of the tank's evolution, a number of armored transport vehicles appeared, such as armoured personnel carriers and amphibious vehicles.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] After the war ended, armored transports continued to evolve.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The armored car and train declined in use, largely becoming relegated to military and civilian use as transportation for VIPs.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Infantry fighting vehicles rose to prominence with the creation of the Soviet BMP-1.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] IFVs are a more combat capable version of the APC, with heavier armaments (such as autocannons), while still retaining the ability to transport combatants into and out of battles.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Sealift is a military logistics term referring to the use of cargo ships for the deployment of military assets, such as weaponry, military personnel, and materiel supplies.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] It complements other means of transport, such as strategic airlifters, in order to enhance a state's ability to project power.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] A state's sealift capabilities may include civilian-operated ships that normally operate by contract, but which can be chartered or commandeered during times of military necessity to supplement government-owned naval fleets.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] During WWI, the United States bought, borrowed or commandeered vessels of various types, ranging from pleasure craft to ocean liners to transport the American Expeditionary Force to Europe.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Many of these ships were scrapped, sold or returned to their owners after the war.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] There are two different kinds of airlifts in warfare, a strategic airlift and a tactical airlift.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] A strategic airlift is the use transporting of weapons, supplies and personnel over long distances (from a base in one country to a base in another country for example) using large cargo aircraft.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] This contrasts with tactical airlifts, which involves transporting the same above items within a theater of operations.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] This usually involves cargo planes with shorter ranges and slower speeds, but higher maneuverability.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Land warfare, as the name implies, takes place on land.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The most common type of warfare, it can encompass several modes and locales, including urban, arctic, and mountain warfare.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The early part of the 19th century from 1815 to 1848 saw a long period of peace in Europe, accompanied by extraordinary industrial expansion.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The industrial age brought about various technological advancements, each with their own implication.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Land warfare moved from visual-range and semi person-to-person combat of the previous era, to indiscriminate and impersonal, "beyond visual range" warfare.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The Crimean War (1853–1856) saw the introduction of trench warfare, long-range artillery, railroads, the telegraph, and the rifle.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The mechanized mass-destruction of enemy combatants grew ever more deadly.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In WWI (1914–1918) machine-guns, barbed wire, chemical weapons, and land-mines entered the battlefield.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The deadly stalemated trench-warfare stage was finally passed with the advent of the modern armored tank late in WWI.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] One major trend involved the transition away massed infantry fire and human waves to more refined tactics.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] This became possible with the superseding of earlier weapons like the highly inaccurate musket.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Static defenses evolved from the use of permanent fortifications that were direct descendants of medieval castles.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] As artillery improved in destructive power and penetrative ability, more modern fortifications were developed, using first thicker layers of stone, then concrete and steel.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] After naval artillery developed the turret – a moving cannon platform – land fortifications started to use this method as well.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Between the World Wars, France built an "impregnable" underground steel and concrete fortification that ran the length of the German-French border.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] This Maginot Line failed to stop German tanks in 1940: they bypassed the fortifications by invading through neighboring Belgium.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] As artillery and rifles allowed the killing of enemy personnel at a longer effective range, soldiers started to dig into temporary fortifications.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] These included massive trenches as used in WWI, and individual soldier-sized "fox holes" which became more common in WWII.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Maneuver had existed throughout military history – from soldiers marching on the field to using horses in cavalry formations.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] It was not until the advent of mechanized transport over unprepared terrain, such as fields and deserts, using tanks and armored vehicles, that "maneuver warfare" became feasible.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] First used by the German army in Poland and France in WWII, Blitzkrieg or "lightning war" saw whole armies moved rapidly on tracked and armored fighting vehicles.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] During the war airborne movement was used, with soldiers dropped to the battlefield by parachute by both the Germans and the Allies.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] After WWII, developments in helicopters brought a more practical way to transport troops by air.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The famous battle of the CSS *Virginia* and USS *Monitor* in the American Civil War was the duel of ironclads that symbolized the changing times.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Although the battle was inconclusive, nations around the world subsequently raced to convert their fleets to iron, as ironclads had shown themselves to be clearly superior to wooden ships in their ability to withstand enemy fire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In the late 19th century, naval warfare was revolutionized by Alfred Thayer Mahan's book *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Mahan argued that in the Anglo-French wars of the 18th and 19th centuries, domination of the sea was the deciding factor in the outcome, and therefore control of seaborne commerce was critical to military victory.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Mahan argued that the best way to achieve naval domination was through large fleets of concentrated capital ships, as opposed to commerce raiders.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] His books were closely studied in all the Great Powers, influencing their naval arms race in the years prior to WWI.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] As the century came to a close, the familiar modern battleship began to emerge; a steel-armored ship, entirely dependent on steam turbines, and sporting a number of large shell guns mounted in turrets arranged along the centerline of the main deck.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The ultimate design was reached in 1906 with HMS *Dreadnought*, which entirely dispensed with smaller guns, her main guns being sufficient to sink any existing ship of the time.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The Russo-Japanese War and particularly the Battle of Tsushima in 1905 was the first test of the new concepts, resulting in a stunning Japanese victory and the destruction of dozens of Russian ships.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] World War I pitted the old Royal Navy against the new navy of Imperial Germany, culminating in the 1916 Battle of Jutland.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Following the war, many nations agreed to limit the size of their fleets in the Washington Naval Treaty and scrapped many of their battleships and cruisers.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Growing tensions of the 1930s restarted the building programs, with even larger ships than before: the Japanese battleship *Yamato*, launched in 1941, displaced 72,000 tons and mounted 18-inch (46 cm) guns.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] This marked the climax of "big gun" warfare, as aircraft would gradually play a larger role in warfare.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] By the 1960s, battleships had all-but vanished from the fleets of the world.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Between the world wars, the first aircraft carriers appeared, initially as a way to circumvent the tonnage limits of the Washington Naval Treaty (many of the first carriers were converted battlecruisers).
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Though several ships had previously been designed to launch aircraft, the first true "flat-top" carrier was HMS *Argus*, launched in December 1917.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] By the start of WWII, aircraft carriers typically carried three types of aircraft: torpedo bombers, which could also be used for conventional horizontal bombing and reconnaissance; dive bombers, also used for reconnaissance; and fighters for fleet defence and bomber escort duties.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Because of the restricted space on aircraft carriers, these aircraft were almost always small, single-engined warplanes.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The first true demonstration of naval air power was the victory of the Royal Navy at the Battle of Taranto in 1940, which set the stage for Japan's much larger and more famous attack on Pearl Harbor the following year.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Two days after Pearl Harbor, the sinking of HMS *Prince of Wales* and HMS *Repulse*, marked the beginning of the end for the battleship era.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Following WWII, aircraft carriers continued to remain key to navies throughout the latter 20th century, moving in the 1950s to jets launched from Supercarriers, behemoths which could displace as much as 100,000 tons.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Just as important was the development of submarines to travel underneath the sea, at first for short dives, then later to be able to spend weeks or months underwater powered by a nuclear reactor.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The first successful submarine attack in wartime was in 1864 by the Confederate submarine *H.L.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Hunley* which sank the frigate USS *Housatonic*.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In both World Wars, submarines primarily exerted their power by sinking merchant ships using torpedoes, in addition to attacks on warships.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] All nations practiced unrestricted submarine warfare in which submarines sank merchant ships without warning, but the only successful campaign during this period was America's submarine war against Japan during the Pacific War.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In the 1950s the Cold War inspired the development of ballistic missile submarines, each one loaded with dozens of nuclear-armed missiles and with orders to launch them from sea should the other nation attack.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The first use of airplanes in war was the Italo-Turkish War of 1911, when the Italians carried out several reconnaissance and bombing missions.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] During WWI both sides made use of balloons and airplanes for reconnaissance and directing artillery fire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] To prevent enemy reconnaissance, some airplane pilots began attacking other airplanes and balloons, first with small arms carried in the cockpit, and later with machine guns mounted on the aircraft.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Both sides also made use of aircraft for bombing, strafing and dropping of propaganda leaflets.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The German air force carried out the first terror bombing raids, using Zeppelins to drop bombs on Britain.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] By the end of the war airplanes had become specialised into bombers, fighters, and surveillance aircraft.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Most of these airplanes were biplanes with wooden frames, canvas skins, wire rigging and air-cooled engines.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Between 1918 and 1939, aircraft technology developed very rapidly.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] By 1939 military biplanes were in the process of being replaced with metal framed monoplanes, often with stressed skins and liquid cooled engines.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Top speeds had tripled; altitudes doubled (and oxygen masks become commonplace); ranges and payloads of bombers increased enormously.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Some theorists, most famously Hugh Trenchard and Giulio Douhet, believed that aircraft would become the dominant military arm in the future, and argued that future wars would be won entirely by the destruction of the enemy's military and industrial capability from the air.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] This concept was called strategic bombing.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Others, such as Billy Mitchell, saw the potential of air power to neutralize the striking power of naval surface fleets.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Mitchell himself proved the vulnerability of capital ships to aircraft was finally in 1921 when he commanded a squadron of bombers that sank the ex-German battleship SMS *Ostfriesland* with aerial bombs.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] During WWII, there was a debate between strategic bombing and tactical bombing.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Tactical bombing focused on concentration of combatants, command and control centers, airfields, and ammunition dumps, and required attack aircraft, dive bombers, and fighter bombers that could fly low over the battlefield.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In the early years of WWII, the German *Luftwaffe* focused on tactical bombing, using large numbers of Ju 87 Stukas as "flying artillery" for land offensives.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Artillery was slow and required time to set up a firing position, whereas aircraft were better able keep up with the fast advances of the German panzer columns.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Close air support greatly assisted in the successes of the German Army in the Battle of France.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] It was also important in amphibious warfare, where aircraft carriers could provide support for soldiers landing on the beaches.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Strategic bombing, by contrast, was unlike anything the world has seen before or since.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In 1940, the Germans attempted to force Britain to surrender through attacks on its airfields and factories, and then on its cities in The Blitz in what became the Battle of Britain, the first major battle whose outcome was determined primarily in the air.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The campaigns conducted in Europe and Asia could involve thousands of aircraft dropping tens of thousands of tons of munitions over a single city.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Military aviation in the post-war years was dominated by the needs of the Cold War.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The postwar years saw a rapid conversion to jet power, which resulted in enormous increases in speeds and altitudes of aircraft.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Until the advent of the intercontinental ballistic missile, major powers relied on high-altitude bombers to deliver their newly developed nuclear deterrent.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Each country strove to develop the technology of bombers and the high-altitude fighters that could intercept them.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The concept of air superiority began to play a heavy role in aircraft designs for both the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The use of nuclear weapons first came into being during the last months of WWII, with the dropping of atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] This was the only use of nuclear weapons in combat.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] For a decade after World War II, the United States and later the Soviet Union (and to a lesser extent the United Kingdom and France) developed and maintained a strategic force of bombers that would be able to attack any potential aggressor from bases inside their countries.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Before the development of a capable strategic missile force in the Soviet Union, much of the war-fighting doctrine held by western nations revolved around the use of a large number of smaller nuclear weapons used in a tactical role.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] It is arguable if such use could be considered "limited" however, because it was believed that the US would use their own strategic weapons (mainly bombers at the time) should the USSR deploy any kind of nuclear weapon against civilian targets.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] A revolution in thinking occurred with the introduction of the intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM), which the Soviet Union first successfully tested in the late 1950s.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] To deliver a warhead to a target, a missile was far less expensive than a bomber that could do the same job.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Moreover, at the time it was impossible to intercept ICBMs due to their high altitude and speed.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In the 1960s, another major shift in nuclear doctrine occurred with the development of the submarine-based nuclear missile (SLBM).
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] It was hailed by military theorists as a weapon that would assure a surprise attack would not destroy the capability to retaliate, and therefore would make nuclear war less likely.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Since the end of WWII, no industrial nations have fought such a large, decisive war, due to the availability of weapons that are so destructive that their use would offset the advantages of victory.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The fighting of a total war where nuclear weapons are used is something that instead of taking years and the full mobilisation of a country's resources such as in WWII, would take tens of minutes.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Such weapons are developed and maintained with relatively modest peace time defence budgets.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] By the end of the 1950s, the ideological stand-off of the Cold War between the Western World and the Soviet Union involved thousands of nuclear weapons being aimed at each side by the other.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Strategically, the equal balance of destructive power possessed by each side situation came to be known as Mutually Assured Destruction (MAD), the idea that a nuclear attack by one superpower would result in nuclear counter-strike by the other.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] This would result in hundreds of millions of deaths in a world where, in words widely attributed to Nikita Khrushchev, "The living will envy the dead".
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] During the Cold War, the superpowers sought to avoid open conflict between their respective forces, as both sides recognized that such a clash could very easily escalate, and quickly involve nuclear weapons.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Instead, the superpowers fought each other through their involvement in proxy wars, military buildups, and diplomatic standoffs.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] In the case of proxy wars, each superpower supported its respective allies in conflicts with forces aligned with the other superpower, such as in the Korean War, the Vietnam War, and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] Non nuclear nations still fought industrialized warfare as the long Iran–Iraq War that ended in a trench warfare stalemate.
[src:battle-of-sinop/19th-century-warfare] The Royal United Services Institute stated that the Russo-Ukrainian War has proven that the age of industrial warfare is still here and that massive consumption of equipment, vehicles and ammunition requires a large industrial base for resupply.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdulmejid's greatest achievement was the announcement of the Tanzimat Edict upon his accession, prepared by his then Foreign Minister Mustafa Reshid Pasha, which effectively began the Tanzimat era, or era of reorganization, in the Ottoman Empire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] He was a mild-mannered monarch, giving the Sublime Porte the autonomy needed for its reform projects.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] One of the main goals of the Tanzimat was to encourage Ottomanism among the millets to stop rising nationalist movements within the empire, but despite new laws and reforms to integrate non-Muslims and non-Turks more thoroughly into Ottoman society, in the long term, the movement failed.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdulmejid forged alliances with the major powers of Western Europe, namely the United Kingdom and France, which fought alongside the Ottoman Empire in the Crimean War against Russia.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] During the Congress of Paris on 30 March 1856, the Ottoman Empire was officially included among the Concert of Europe.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdulmejid suddenly died of tuberculosis and was succeeded by his half-brother, Abdul Aziz.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdülmecid was born on 25 April 1823 at Beşiktaş Palace or at Topkapı Palace, in Istanbul.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] His mother was the Georgian consort Bezmiâlem Kadın.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdülmecid received a European education and was the first sultan to speak fluent French.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Like Abdülaziz who succeeded him, he was interested in literature and classical music.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] When Abdülmecid acceded to the throne on 2 July 1839, he was only sixteen and inexperienced, and the affairs of the Ottoman Empire were in a critical state.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] His father Mahmud II died at the start of the Second Egyptian–Ottoman War, the news reached Istanbul that the empire's army had just been defeated at Nizip by the army of the rebel Egyptian viceroy, Muhammad Ali.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] At the same time, the empire's fleet was on its way to Alexandria, where it was handed over to Muhammad Ali by its commander Ahmed Fevzi Pasha on the pretext that the young sultan's advisers had sided with Russia.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] However, through the intervention of the European powers during the Oriental Crisis of 1840, Muhammad Ali was obliged to come to terms, and the Ottoman Empire was saved from further attacks while its territories in Syria, Lebanon and Palestine were restored.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The terms were finalised at the Convention of London (1840) which saved the empire from greater embarrassment.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Like his father, Abdülmecid was an advocate of reforms and was lucky enough to have the support of progressive viziers such as Mustafa Reşit Pasha, Mehmet Emin Âli Pasha and Fuad Pasha.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdülmecid was also the first sultan to listen directly to the public's complaints on special reception days, which were usually held every Friday.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdülmecid toured the empire's territories to see in person how the Tanzimat reforms were being applied.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] He travelled to İzmit, Mudanya, Bursa, Gallipoli, Çanakkale, Lemnos, Lesbos and Chios in 1844 and toured the Balkan provinces in 1846.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] In compliance with his father's express instructions, Abdülmecid immediately carried out the reforms to which Mahmud II had devoted himself.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] On 3 November 1839, the Edict of Gülhane, also known as Tanzimat Fermanı, was proclaimed, consolidating and enforcing these reforms.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] By these enactments it was provided that the sultan's subjects of all classes should have their lives and property protected; that taxes should be fairly imposed and justice impartially administered; and that all should have full religious liberty and equal civil rights.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The scheme met with strong opposition from the Muslim governing classes and the *ulema,* or religious authorities, and was only partially implemented, especially in the more remote parts of the empire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] More than one conspiracy was formed against the sultan's life on account of it.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The 1840s saw the creation of the first banknotes and the establishment of the Ottoman lira.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The financial system was reorganised after the French model.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Tax farming was abolished and aşar was to be equally levied everywhere.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Plans were also set to abolish slave markets.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] After the Imperial Reform Edict, further reforms towards equality between millets were implemented, including the abolition of a capitation tax which imposed higher tariffs on non-Muslims and the right to serve as soldiers in the Ottoman army.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Other French-inspired reforms included the reorganization of the Civil and Criminal Code and the reorganization of education.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The General Council of Education (*Meclis-i Maarif-i Umumiye*) was created in 1841, followed by the Ministry of Education.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] A new system of civil and criminal courts was established with both European and Ottoman judges.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The first modern universities and academies in the European tradition were established in 1848, coinciding with the founding of an Ottoman school in Paris.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Many army reforms were also implemented in the early 1840s, including the introduction of conscription.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] In 1844, an Ottoman national flag was adopted and Abdul Mecid's anthem was adopted as the Ottoman imperial anthem.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] In 1853 the General Council of Reorganization (*Meclis-i Âli-i Tanzimat*) was established.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Two representatives from each eyalet were summoned to a council to report the needs of their region.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] This was the prototype of the First Ottoman Parliament (1876).
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Another notable reform was that the turban was officially outlawed for the first time during Abdülmecid's reign, in favour of the fez.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] European fashions were also adopted by the Court.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] (The fez would be banned in 1925 by the same Republican National Assembly that abolished the sultanate and proclaimed the Turkish Republic in 1923).
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] When Lajos Kossuth and his comrades sought refuge in Turkey after the failure of the Hungarian Revolution of 1848, the sultan was called on by Austria and Russia to surrender them, but he refused.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] On 16 October 1853, the Ottoman Empire entered another war against Russia that would be known as the Crimean War, where it was soon joined by France and Britain.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The Ottomans successfully participated in the war and were winning signatories at the Treaty of Paris (1856).
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The Empire would be inducted into the Concert of Europe.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] In a compromise with the Great Powers, Abdul Mecid issued another reform edict in February 1856 known as the Imperial Reform Edict (Islâhat Hatt-ı Hümâyûnu), which was perceived by many subjects as relinquishing sovereignty.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The Ottoman Empire received the first of its foreign loans on 25 August 1854 during the war.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] This major foreign loan was followed by those of 1855, 1858 and 1860, which culminated in default and led to the alienation of European sympathy from the Ottoman Empire and indirectly to the later dethronement and death of Abdülmecid's brother Abdülaziz.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Financial troubles and the discontent caused by the wide privileges given to the non-Muslim subjects again led to the empire becoming unstable.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] His attempts at strengthening his base in the Balkans were overshadowed by incidents that took place in Montenegro in 1858 and Bosnia.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] In 1861 he was forced to give up Lebanon through the creation of the Mutasarrifate of Mount Lebanon.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The major European states had taken the opportunity to intervene in their own interests.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Ottoman statesmen panicked in the face of this situation.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The fact that Abdülmecid could not prevent this situation further increased the dissatisfaction caused by the Edict of Tanzimat.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The opponents formed the Society of Fedâis, which sought to eliminate Abdülmecid and put Abdulaziz on the throne in order to prevent the European states from acting like a guardian.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] This revolt attempt, the Kuleli Incident, was suppressed before it even started on 14 September 1859.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Meanwhile, the financial situation deteriorated and foreign debts, which were taken under heavy conditions to cover the costs of war, placed a burden on the treasury.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] All of the debts received from Beyoğlu consumers exceeded eighty million gold liras.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Some of the debt securities and hostages were taken by foreign traders and bankers.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The Grand Vizier Mehmed Emin Âli Pasha, who criticized this situation harshly, was dismissed by the sultan on 18 October 1859.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The Egyptian governor Mehmed Ali Pasha, who came to Istanbul on the official invitation of the sultan on 19 July 1846, was shown privileged hospitality by the sultan and the vükela (government ministers).
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] So much so that the old vizier built the Galata bridge in 1845 so that he could drive between Beșiktaș Palace and Bab-ı Ali.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Although he emphasized his commitment to the ceremonial rules imposed by his ancestors at the ceremonies reflected outside, he adopted radical changes in the life of the palace.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] For example, he abandoned the Topkapı Palace, which the Ottoman dynasty had used for four centuries, and constructed the more modern Dolmabahçe Palace.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Between 1847 and 1849 he had repairs made to the Hagia Sophia mosque.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] He also founded the first French Theatre in Istanbul.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Many reconstruction activities were also carried out during the reign of Abdülmecid.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Palaces and mansions were built with some of the borrowed money.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] An addition to Dolmabahçe Palace (1853), Beykoz Pavilion (1855), Küçüksu Pavilion (1857), Küçük Mecidiye Mosque (1849), Teşvikiye Mosque (1854) are among the main architectural works of the period.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Again in this period, as was done by Bezmiâlem Sultan's Gureba Hospital (1845-1846), the new Galata Bridge was put into service on the same date.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] In addition, many fountains, mosques, lodges and similar social institutions were repaired or rebuilt.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdülmecid died of tuberculosis (like his father) at the age of 38 on 25 June 1861 in Istanbul, and was buried in Yavuz Selim Mosque, and was succeeded by his younger half-brother Sultan Abdulaziz, son of Pertevniyal Sultan.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] At the time of his death, Abdülmecid had one legal wife and queen consort, Perestu Kadın, and many concubines.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdülmecid was known for his clemency, even refusing to sanction the execution of those who conspired against his life.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] The 1911 *Encyclopædia Britannica* says of him, "He bore the character of being a kind and honourable man, if somewhat weak and easily led.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] Abdülmecid had one of the most numerous harems of the dynasty.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] He is known to be the first sultan whose harem was not composed of slave girls but, due to the progressive abolition of slavery in the Ottoman Empire, of girls of free birth, noble or bourgeois, sent to the sultan by the will of the families.
[src:battle-of-sinop/abdulmecid-i] He was also the first sultan whose harem assumed a defined hierarchical structure which included four Kadın, followed by four Ikbal, four gözde and a variable number of minor concubines.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The **Adana campaign** occurred after Ottoman forces seized the city of Adana from the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The Mamluks responded by sending a force under Commander and Chief Uzbek, and besieged Adana.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The Ottomans responded by sending a large relief force that was defeated.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The Ottoman Empire had launched a campaign in 1485 against the Mamluk holdings in Southern Turkey and in Cicilia Armenia, seizing areas such as Adana.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The Mamluk Forces in the Taurus Mountains withdrew to Aleppo.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] In order to respond, Sultan Qaitbey had Atabeg Uzbek launch a counter offensive.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] To this cause Qaitbey had granted Uzbek 3,000 Royal Mamluks as well as Nine of the 15 Emirs of 1,000.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The force set off from Cairo over Damascus to Aleppo, recruiting local Syrian peasants along the way.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] In February the Mamluks arrived at Adana.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] After a peace message by Uzbek was ignored, the Mamluks confronted an Ottoman force outside the city.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The Ottomans were quickly routed, with many fleeing.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] Around 800 were captured, including 17 commanders and paraded in Damascus, Aleppo, and Cairo.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] After the battle, the Mamluks besieged Adana.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] When Sultan Bayezid II learned of the offensive on Adana, he sent Hersek-oglu to lead an Ottoman army to relieve Adana.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] Hersek-oglu was the son of Stjepan Vukčić, Duke of Herzegovina, who was sent as a hostage to the court of Mehmed II.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] When Bayezid seized power, he allowed Kersek-oglu to marry one of his daughters, and also granted him a high position.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] When Hersek-oglu's approached the Mamluk Army, his reconnaissance unit was routed by the Mamluks.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The survivors managed to report that the Mamluks had less than 15,000 soldiers.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] There, Hersek-oglu's forces suffered a massive defeat.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The Turkmen contingents fled during the beginning of the battle.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] Hersek-oglu and 200 of his Janissaries fought on, despite being encircled.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] He was wounded and captured by the Mamluks.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] Among the captives were also the son of the late vezir Mustafa Pasha, Kiral-oglu, (son of Isfendiyar-oğlu) Kızıl Ahmed, (Sanjakbegi of Kengırı) Ahmed Beg, and the sultan's chief pantry-keeper (kilerjibaşı) Süleyman Aga.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] After the battle, the Adana garrison of 1,500 fighters also surrendered.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The Ottoman prisoners were sent to Syria.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] The Mamluk victory allowed the Mamluks to re-establish control of Tartus and Adana.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adana-campaign] Despite attempts to broker peace by the Mamluks, the Ottomans would continue to launch further offensives which would eventually lead to the Ottoman conquest of Cilicia.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The word *admiral* in Middle English comes from Anglo-French *amiral*, "commander", from Medieval Latin *admiralis*, *admirallus*.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The 1818 edition of Samuel Johnson's *A Dictionary of the English Language*, edited and revised by the Rev.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The quote from John Minsheu's Dictionarie in Spanish and English (1599), given in Johnson's Dictionary, has been confirmed as being accurate.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] Those Phanariots who attained the princely position of dragoman of the fleet served under the Ottoman admiral having administration of the Aegean islands and the Anatolian coast.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] Central Command, introduced Vice Admiral Mark I.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] One alternate etymology proposes that the term admiral evolved, instead, from the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ (أمير الأمراء).
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] Under the reign of the Buyid dynasty (934 to 1062) of Iraq and Iran, the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ, which means prince of princes, came to denote the heir-apparent, or crown prince.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] This alternate etymology states that the term was in use for the Greco-Arab naval leaders (e.g.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] Christodulus) in the Norman-Arab-Byzantine culture of Norman Sicily, which had formerly been ruled by Arabs, at least by the early 11th century.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] During this time, the Norman Roger II of Sicily (1095–1154) employed a Greek Christian, known as George of Antioch, who previously had served as a naval commander for several North African Muslim rulers.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] Roger styled George in Abbasid fashion as *Amir of Amirs*, or Amīr al-Umarāʾ, with the title becoming Latinized in the 13th century as *ammiratus ammiratorum*.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The Sicilians and later the Genoese took the first two parts of the term from their Aragon opponents and used them as one word, *amiral*. .
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The French gave their sea commanders similar titles while in Portuguese and Spanish the word changed to *almirante*.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] As the word was used by people speaking Latin or Latin-based languages it gained the "d" and endured a series of different endings and spellings leading to the English spelling *admyrall* in the 14th century and to *admiral* by the 16th century.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The etymology of a word does not suggest the antiquity of the word as it may have appeared in other languages with entirely different pronunciations.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The Greek ναύαρχος, for instance, which is pronounced "naúarkhos", existed from very ancient times in Greece.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The word "admiral" has come to be almost exclusively associated with the highest naval rank in most of the world's navies, equivalent to the army rank of general.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] However, this was not always the case; for example, in some European countries prior to the end of World War II, admiral was the third highest naval rank after general admiral and grand admiral.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The rank of admiral has also been subdivided into various grades, several of which are historically extinct while others remain in use in most present-day navies.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The Royal Navy used the colours red, white, and blue, in descending order to indicate seniority of its admirals until 1864; for example, Horatio Nelson's highest rank was vice-admiral of the white.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] The generic term for these naval equivalents of army generals is flag officer.
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] Some navies have also used army-type titles for them, such as the Cromwellian "general at sea".
[src:battle-of-sinop/admiral] While the rank is used in most of NATO countries, it is ranked differently depending on the country.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adolphus-slade] Admiral **Sir Adolphus Slade** CB (1804 – 13 November 1877) was a British admiral who became an admiral in the Ottoman Navy.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adolphus-slade] He was the fifth son of General Sir John Slade.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Some polities adopted the new calendar in 1582, others not before the early twentieth century, and others at various dates between.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] A few have yet to do so, but except for these, the Gregorian Calendar is now the universal civil calendar, yet old style calendars remain in use in religious or traditional contexts.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] During – and for some time after – the transition between systems, it has been common to use the terms "Old Style" and "New Style" in dating to indicate which calendar was used to reckon them.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Pope Gregory XIII instituted the Gregorian Calendar in 1582 by the Papal bull *Inter gravissimas* to correct an error in the Julian Calendar that was causing an erroneous calculation of the date of Easter.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Julian Calendar had been based on a year of 365.25 days, but this was slightly too long; in reality it is circa 365.2422 days, and so over centuries the Calendar had drifted increasingly out of alignment with the orbit of Earth.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] According to Gregory's scientific advisors, the Calendar had acquired 10 excess leap days since the First Council of Nicaea, which established the rule for dating Easter in AD 325.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Consequently, he ruled, the numbering, i. e. dating, of days must jump by 10 to restore the *status quo ante*; thus, for example, when the Catholic polities of Europe adopted the Gregorian Calendar, the day after Thursday, 4 October 1582 was dated as Friday, 15 October 1582.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Polities that did not change calendars until the 18th century had by then observed 1700 as an additional leap year, necessitating the omission of 11 dates from the reckoning.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Some polities did not change until the 19th or 20th centuries, necessitating the omission of 12 or 13 dates.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Although Gregory's reform was instituted in the most solemn of forms available to the Church, the bull had no authority beyond ecclesial institutions and the Papal States.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The changes he proposed were to the civil calendar, which was not directly subject to Papal authority.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] For these changes to be legally effectuated, the civil authority of each polity was needed.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The bull became canon law of the Catholic Church in 1582, but Protestant churches, Eastern Orthodox Churches, and a few others did not effectuate it, and therefore the dates on which different Christian denominations celebrated Easter and other holidays diverged.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Philip II of Spain decreed the change from the Julian to Gregorian Calendar, which affected much of Catholic Europe, as Philip was at the time ruler of Spain–Portugal and much of modern Italy.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] France adopted the new calendar with Sunday, 9 December 1582 being succeeded by Monday, 20 December 1582.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Dutch provinces of Brabant and Zeeland, and the States General adopted it on 25 December of that year; the provinces forming the Southern Netherlands (modern Belgium) except the Duchy of Brabant adopted it on 1 January 1583; the province of Holland adopted it on 12 January 1583.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The seven Catholic Swiss cantons adopted the new calendar in January 1584.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Many Protestant polities initially objected to adoption of a Catholic innovation; some Protestants feared the new calendar was part of a plot to return them to the Catholic fold.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In the Czech Lands, Protestants resisted the Gregorian Calendar that the Habsburg monarchy imposed.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In 1700, through Ole Rømer's influence, Denmark–Norway adopted the solar portion of the Gregorian calendar simultaneously with the Brandenburg-Pomerania and other Protestant estates of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Sunday, 18 February 1700, was followed by Monday, 1 March 1700.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] They finally adopted the Gregorian calculation of Easter in 1774.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The remaining provinces of the Dutch Republic adopted the Gregorian calendar on 12 July 1700 (Gelderland), 12 December 1700 (Overijssel and Utrecht), 12 January 1701 (Friesland and Groningen) and 12 May 1701 (Drenthe).
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Through enactment of the Calendar (New Style) Act 1750, Great Britain and its possessions (including parts of what is now the United States) adopted the Gregorian calendar in 1752, by which time it was necessary to correct by 11 days.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Wednesday, 2 September 1752, was followed by Thursday, 14 September 1752.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In Great Britain, the term "New Style" was used for the calendar and the Act omits any acknowledgement of Pope Gregory: the Annexe to the Act established a computation for the date of Easter that achieved the same result as Gregory's rules, without actually referring to him.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] With the same Act, the Empire (except Scotland, which had already done so from 1600) changed the start of the civil year from 25 March to 1 January.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Consequently, the custom of dual dating (giving a date in both old and new styles) can refer to the Julian/Gregorian calendar change, or to the start of year change, or to both.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Lutheran Duchy of Prussia, until 1657 still a fiefdom of Catholic Poland, was the first Protestant state to adopt the Gregorian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Under the influence of its liege lord, the King of Poland, it agreed in 1611 to do so.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] So 22 August was followed by 2 September 1612.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] However, this calendar change did not apply to other territories of the Hohenzollern, such as Berlin-based Brandenburg, a fief of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Sweden's transition to the Gregorian calendar was difficult and protracted.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Sweden started to make the change from the Julian calendar and towards the Gregorian calendar in 1700, but it was decided to make the (then 11-day) adjustment gradually by excluding the leap days (29 February) from each of 11 successive leap years, 1700 to 1740.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Meanwhile, the Swedish calendar would be out of step with both the Julian calendar and the Gregorian calendar for 40 years; also, the difference would not be constant but would change every four years.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] This system had the potential for confusion when working out the dates of Swedish events in this 40-year period.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] To add to the confusion, the system was poorly administered, and the leap days that should have been excluded in 1704 and 1708 were not excluded.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Swedish calendar (according to the transition plan) should have been 8 days behind the Gregorian but was 10 days behind.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] King Charles XII recognised that the gradual change to the new system was not working, and he abandoned it.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Rather than proceeding directly to the Gregorian calendar, it was decided to revert to the Julian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] This was achieved by introducing the unique date 30 February in 1712, adjusting the discrepancy in the calendars from 10 back to 11 days.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Sweden finally adopted the solar portion of the Gregorian calendar in 1753, when Wednesday, 17 February, was followed by Thursday, 1 March.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] What became later Finland was an integral part of the Swedish kingdom at that time, hence it did the same.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Russian Empire's 1809 conquest of Finland did not revert this, since autonomy was granted, but government documents in Finland were dated in both the Julian and Gregorian styles.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] This practice ended when independence was gained in 1917.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] As noted above, the Catholic cantons of Switzerland adopted the new calendar in 1582.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Geneva and several Protestant cantons adopted it in January 1701 or at other dates throughout the 18th century.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The two Swiss communes of Schiers and Grüsch were the last areas of Western and Central Europe to switch to the Gregorian calendar, in 1812.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Many of the countries of eastern Europe were Eastern Orthodox or Islamic and adopted the Gregorian calendar much later than western Christian countries.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Some religious groups in some of these countries, known as Old Calendarists, still use the "old style" (O.S.) Julian calendar for ecclesiastical purposes.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Kingdom of Bulgaria changed from the Julian to the Gregorian calendar in 1916 during the First World War.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Ottoman Empire's Rumi calendar, used for fiscal purposes, was realigned from a Julian to a Gregorian basis starting on 16 February / 1 March 1917.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The beginning of the year was reset to 1 January starting in 1918.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The numbering of the years, though, remained uniquely Turkish until Turkey adopted the Gregorian calendar on 1 January 1926.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The transition left a visible trace in historical records: gravestones from the early Republican era in cemeteries such as Feriköy Cemetery commonly show birth years in the Hijri calendar and death dates in the Gregorian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Since exact birth dates were often unrecorded and a Hijri year usually spans two Gregorian years, the precise Gregorian birth year cannot be determined from these inscriptions.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In Russia, the Gregorian calendar was accepted after the October Revolution.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] On 24 January 1918, the Council of People's Commissars issued a decree that Wednesday, 31 January 1918, was to be followed by Thursday, 14 February 1918, thus dropping 13 days from the calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The decree required that the Julian date was to be written in parentheses after the Gregorian date, until 1 July 1918.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] With the change, the October Revolution itself, once converted, took place on 7 November.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Articles about the October Revolution that mention this date difference tend to do a full conversion to the dates from Julian to the Gregorian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] For example, in the article "The October (November) Revolution" the *Encyclopædia Britannica* uses the format of "25 October (7 November, New Style)" to describe the date of the start of the revolution.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In the territory of modern Ukraine, the Gregorian calendar was officially adopted for secular use immediately after its adoption by Pope Gregory XIII in 1582, as most of Ukraine then was part of the predominantly Catholic Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Roman Catholic Church in Ukraine switched to the new calendar at the same time.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] However, the Orthodox churches in the Commonwealth refused to accept a calendar instigated by a Roman Catholic Pope, so the Orthodox Church of Ukraine continued following the old Julian calendar until 2023.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In 2018, the Ukrainian Lutheran Church switched to the Revised Julian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] After the Russian invasion in 2022, most other Christian denominations that were still using the old Julian calendar announced that they would transition to the Gregorian or the Revised Julian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The All-Ukrainian Union of Churches of Evangelical Christian Baptists and the Church of Christians of the Evangelical Faith of Ukraine (Pentecostals) switched to the Gregorian calendar the same year.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] On 1 September 2023, the Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church switched to the Gregorian calendar, while the Orthodox Church of Ukraine opted for the Revised Julian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] At the same time, the Ukrainian Orthodox Church (Moscow Patriarchate) declared that it would continue to celebrate the birth of Christ according to the Julian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Other countries of Eastern Europe, most notably Eastern Orthodox countries, adopted the Gregorian calendar for secular purposes in the 1910s or early 1920s.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] By the 20th century, the date on the Julian calendar was 13 days behind that on the Gregorian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Romania adopted the Gregorian in 1919, with 31 March 1919 being followed by 14 April 1919.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The last country of Eastern Orthodox Europe to adopt the Gregorian calendar for secular purposes was Greece, at the time under military administration following the 11 September 1922 Revolution.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] As a consequence, Wednesday 15 February 1923 in the Greek calendar was followed by Thursday 1 March 1923.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The decree expressly limited the reform to lay (i.e. non-religious) matters, so the reform did not affect the dates of religious holidays.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] While the civil administrations of Eastern European countries adopted the Gregorian calendar in the 1910s or early 1920s, none of the national Eastern Orthodox Churches have recognised the Gregorian calendar for church or religious purposes.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Instead, the Revised Julian calendar was proposed in May 1923 at the Council of Constantinople.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] It uses a different leap year rule, leading to the mean year being slightly shorter than that of the Gregorian calendar, while being constructed in such a way as to maximise the time before its dates start to diverge from the Gregorian.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] There will be no difference between the two calendars until 2800.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] This is most interesting in the case of the Syriac Orthodox Church, as one of its Patriarchs, Ignatius Nemet Allah I, was one of the nine scholars who devised the Gregorian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Indian Orthodox Church uses the Gregorian calendar along with their autonomous Syriac Orthodox counterparts in India, the Malankara Jacobite Syriac Orthodox Church.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Armenian Apostolic Church adopted the Gregorian calendar in 1923, except in the Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem, where the old Julian calendar is still in use.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The European colonies of the Americas adopted the change when their mother countries did.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In North America, New France and New Spain had adopted the new calendar in 1582.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The British colonies of Canada and the Thirteen Colonies followed suit in 1752, as declared by the British calendar act.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In the rest of South America, the Portuguese colonies also changed in 1582.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Alaska remained on the Julian calendar along with the rest of Russia until 1867, when the territory was sold to the United States.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] At noon on Saturday, 7 October 1867 (Julian), the date changed to Friday, 18 October 1867 (Gregorian).
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Although the Julian calendar was 12 days behind the Gregorian calendar, only 11 days were skipped because Alaska also moved from the Eurasian side of the International Date Line to the American side.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Japan, Korea, and China started using the Gregorian calendar on 1 January 1873, 1 January 1896, and 1 January 1912, respectively.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] They previously used lunisolar calendars.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Old Style and New Style dates in these countries usually mean the older lunisolar dates and the newer Gregorian calendar dates respectively.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In these countries, the old style calendars were similar but not all the same.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Arabic numerals may be used for both calendar dates in modern Japanese and Korean languages, but not for Chinese old-style dates.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] (The Japanese rendering of the Western months is simply *ichi-gatsu* or "One-month" for January, *ni-gatsu* or "Two-month" for February, etc.) This brought Japan's calendar in alignment with that of the major Western powers (excluding Russia).
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] To this day, however, it is common to use reign names (nengō), especially for official documents; for instance, *Meiji* 1 for 1868, *Taishō* 1 for 1912, *Shōwa* 1 for 1926, *Heisei* 1 for 1989, *Reiwa* 1 for 2019, and so on.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The months and days are those of the Gregorian calendar, but the year is either the "Western calendar" (西暦, *seireki*) year number per the Common Era or Anno Domini system, or a year of the nengō of the emperor on the throne.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Since 1873, an era and the first year of that era has begun on the day of the year that the emperor ascended the throne.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The second year of that era began on the next 1 January even if the first year contained only a few days.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] All subsequent years of that era began on 1 January until that emperor died or abdicated.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] For example, the first year of the Showa Era, that of Emperor Hirohito, contained only the last six days of 1926, while Showa 64, his last year, contained only the first seven days of 1989.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The current Gregorian year 2026 corresponds to Reiwa 8.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Replacing its years numbered from 1392, the founding of the Joseon dynasty, Korea started using the Gregorian calendar on 1 January 1896, which was the 17th day of the 11th lunar month not only in Korea but also in China, which still used the lunisolar calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Yet Korean era names were used for its years through 1910; and between 1910 and 1945, when Korea was under Japanese rule, Japanese era names were used to count the years of the Gregorian calendar used in Korea.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In South Korea, from 1945 until 1961, Gregorian calendar years were also counted from the foundation of Gojoseon in 2333 BC (regarded as year one), the date of the legendary founding of Korea by Dangun, hence these Dangi (단기) years were 4278 to 4294.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] This numbering was informally used with the Korean lunar calendar before 1945 but is only occasionally used today.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Since 1997, North Korea officially counts years based on the Juche era, the first year of which is 1912, the year of Kim Il Sung's birth, with Gregorian months and days.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The current Gregorian year 2026 corresponds to Juche year 115.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] At its founding on 1 January 1912, the Republic of China (ROC) government under Provisional President Sun Yat-sen abolished the lunisolar Chinese calendar and adopted the Gregorian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The public, however, resisted the change and continued to observe traditional holidays.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] President Yuan Shikai switched to a dual-calendar policy, under which the Gregorian calendar was to be used for most purposes except traditional holidays, which were to be timed according to the Chinese calendar; this would also be followed by the short-lived Empire of China.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] With the 1928 unification of China under the Kuomintang, the Nationalist government decreed that, effective 1 January 1929, the Gregorian calendar would be used.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The current Gregorian year 2026 corresponds to the ROC year 115.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] This system is still in use in Taiwan where the ROC government retains control since 1945.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Upon its foundation in 1949, the People's Republic of China continued to use the Gregorian calendar with numbered months and adopted Western numbered years, but timed traditional holidays according to the Chinese calendar and abolished the ROC Era System.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Today mainland China (including Hong Kong and Macau), Taiwan, Malaysia, Indonesia and Singapore all observe traditional holidays based on the traditional calendar, such as Chinese New Year, while timing other holidays, especially national anniversaries, according to the Gregorian calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The adopted calendar in both mainland China and Taiwan is called the *Public Calendar* (simplified Chinese: 公历; traditional Chinese: 公曆; pinyin: *Gōnglì*), or "New Calendar" (simplified Chinese: 新历; traditional Chinese: 新曆; pinyin: *Xīnlì*).
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In speaking, people generally call the date in the Gregorian calendar month "No.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] *dd*" (simplified Chinese: dd号; traditional Chinese: dd號); for example, the Spring Festival of year 2017 is No.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] 28 of Month 1 (simplified Chinese: 1月28号; traditional Chinese: 1月28號).
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] On the other hand, people never call dates on the Chinese calendar as "No.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] *dd".*, which avoids any possible ambiguity.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] When referencing dates before the introduction of the Gregorian calendar in 1582, the official Chinese calendar may either inherit the issues with earlier calendars to be historically correct or follow the proleptic Gregorian calendar if so specified.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Vietnam adopted the Gregorian calendar in 1954, replacing the Vietnamese calendar, which was based on the Chinese calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Like China, Vietnam still uses the Vietnamese calendar to observe lunisolar holidays and celebrations.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Gregorian calendar replaced the Burmese calendar in several mainland Southeast Asian kingdoms in the second half of the 19th century.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] This took place in Cambodia in 1863 and Laos in 1889.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Since the British conquest of the Konbaung dynasty in 1886, the Gregorian calendar has been used alongside the Burmese calendar in Myanmar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] In 1889, Siam also switched to the Gregorian calendar as the official civil calendar, with the Rattanakosin Era (with 1782 as Year 1).
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The Thai lunar calendar remains in use for religious purposes.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The lunar Higri calendar (commonly known in the West as the "Islamic calendar" because it is used by the majority of Muslims) has a year of twelve lunar months in a year of 354 or 355 days, being 11 days shorter than a solar year.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Consequently, holy days in Sunni Islam migrate around the solar year on a 32-year cycle.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Some countries in the Islamic world use the Gregorian calendar for civil purposes, while retaining the Islamic calendar for religious purposes.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] For example, Saudi Arabia adopted the Gregorian calendar for the purpose of paying public sector staff effective 1 October 2016; private sector employers had already adopted the Gregorian calendar for pay purposes.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Today, the vast majority of countries use the Gregorian calendar as their sole civil calendar.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The four countries which have not adopted the Gregorian calendar are Ethiopia (Ethiopian calendar), Nepal (Vikram Samvat and Nepal Sambat), Iran and Afghanistan (Solar Hijri calendar).
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] While many religious organizations reckon their liturgical year by the Gregorian civil calendar, others have retained their own calendars.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] Alternative calendars are used in many regions of the world today to mark cycles of religious and astrological events.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The use of different calendars had the potential to cause confusion between contemporaries.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] For example, it is related that one of the contributory factors for Napoleon's victory at the Battle of Austerlitz was the confusion between the Russians, who were using the Julian calendar, and the Austrians, who were using the Gregorian calendar, over the date that their forces should combine.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The date when each country adopted the Gregorian calendar, or an equivalent, is marked against a horizontal timeline.
[src:battle-of-sinop/adoption-of-the-gregorian-calendar] The vertical axis is used for expansion to show separate national names for ease in charting, but otherwise has no significance.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:battle-of-sinop/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The **Battle of Sinop**, or the **Battle of Sinope**, was a naval battle that took place on 30 November 1853 between Imperial Russia and the Ottoman Empire during the opening phase of the Crimean War (1853–1856).
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] It took place at Sinop, a sea port on the southern shore of the Black Sea (the northern shore of Anatolian Turkey).
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] A Russian squadron attacked and decisively defeated an Ottoman squadron anchored in Sinop's harbor.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The Russian force consisted of six ships of the line, two frigates and three armed steamers, led by Admiral Pavel Nakhimov; the Ottoman defenders were seven frigates, three corvettes and two armed steamers, commanded by Vice Admiral Osman Pasha.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The Russian navy had recently adopted naval artillery that fired explosive shells, which gave them a decisive advantage in the battle.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] All the Ottoman frigates and corvettes were either sunk or forced to run aground to avoid destruction; only one steamer escaped.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Nearly 3,000 Turks were killed when Nakhimov's forces fired on the town after the battle.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The victory is commemorated in Russia as one of the Days of Military Honour.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The one-sided battle contributed to the decision of France and Britain to enter the war, on the side of the Ottomans.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The battle demonstrated the effectiveness of explosive shells against wooden hulls, and the superiority of shells over cannonballs.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] It led to widespread adoption of explosive naval artillery and indirectly to the development of ironclad warships.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] On 4 October 1853, around 2 months before the battle, in response to the Russian occupation of Moldavia and Wallachia (then part of the Ottoman Danube), the Ottoman Empire declared war on Russia.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] By the early 1850s the Ottoman Empire was deeply in debt and relied exclusively on British and French loans as a means of support.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] As a result, Ottoman leaders had no choice but to agree to drastic reductions in both army and navy force levels.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Tsar Nicholas I saw the reductions as an opportunity to press Russian claims in the Trans-Caucasus and along the Danube River.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] In July 1853 Russian forces occupied several Ottoman principalities and forts along the Danube.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Mediation of the disputes broke down, and Ottoman Sultan Abdulmecid I responded with a declaration of war.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Fearing Russian expansion, the United Kingdom and France issued a concurrent ultimatum: Russia was to fight only defensively.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] As long as Russia stayed on the defensive the Anglo-French would remain neutral, but if Russia acted "aggressively" the western powers reserved the right to get involved.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Hostilities began officially on 4 October, with a principal theater in Europe and another in the Caucasus.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Sultan Abdulmecid ordered an immediate offensive to drive back the Russians and demonstrate Ottoman might before Ottoman finances totally collapsed.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The offensive along the Danube met with mixed success, but the Ottoman land attack into the Russian Caucasus was relatively successful.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] By the end of October, the Russian Caucasus Corps was in danger of being surrounded.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Turkish ships trafficking gunpowder to the Circassians were in contravention of the Straits Convention, which international law was sworn to uphold.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The Russians told the Austrian Consul that they were legitimately entitled to seek redress for this act of piracy.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Furthermore Russia claimed that two Customs House men had been murdered at Tiflis.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The tsar needed no further incentive to react.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Despite the Ottoman declaration of war, the naval aspect was mostly uneventful until November, when the Vice Admiral Osman Pasha was forced to dock at Sinop during a storm on the Black Sea.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] To support the attack and properly supply his forces before significant snowfall, Sultan Abdulmecid ordered a squadron of frigates, steamers and transports to establish a supply corridor to the Ottoman army in Georgia.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Osman Pasha, himself aboard the 60-gun *Avni Illah*, had been sailing with seven frigates, two corvettes and several transports to resupply the Turkish land forces.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Unable to interdict the convoy, Russian naval elements remained in Sevastopol.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Abdulmecid ordered a second convoy commanded by Osman Pasha, but by this time it was late November and the fleet was forced to seek winter quarters.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] It ended up at Sinop, joining the frigate *Kaid Zafer* which had been part of an earlier patrol, and was joined by the steam frigate *Taif* from a smaller squadron.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The Ottomans had wanted to send ships of the line to Sinop, but the British ambassador in Constantinople, Viscount Stratford de Redcliffe, had objected to this plan, and only frigates were sent.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Initial Ottoman activity in the Black Sea had been allowed to proceed unhindered, but as the situation of the Russian Caucasus Corps deteriorated, St.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Pavel Nakhimov was ordered to muster the Russian navy and interdict the Ottomans.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] From 1–23 November Russian squadrons were dispatched into the Black Sea to establish control.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Two Ottoman steamers, the *Medzhir Tadzhiret* and the *Pervaz Bahri*, were captured by the Russians in short engagements.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Russia was able to establish operational control of the sea lanes but storms forced Nakhimov to send back most of his force for repair.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Left with only a frigate, a steamer and three ships of the line, Nakhimov continued the search for Osman and the convoy.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] On 23 November, Osman's flag was sighted returning and then entering the harbor at Sinop.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Nakhimov immediately deployed his ships to blockade the harbor and sent his only frigate to retrieve as many reinforcements as could be found.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] On 30 November, Vice Admiral Fyodor Novosilski rallied six more ships to Nakhimov, completing the blockade force in a loose semi-circle.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Additional steamers were expected, but Nakhimov decided to act before the Ottomans could be reinforced by additional ships.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] For his part, Osman had been well aware of the Russian presence since 23 November, but felt his ships were safe in harbor.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Sinop had substantial harbor defenses and forts with interlocking fields of fire and ample cannon.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Osman did little to break the weak Russian blockade, even allowing many of his crews to disembark.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Three Russian second-rate ships of the line (84 cannons each) led by Admiral Nakhimov arrived at Sinop on 23 November to discover the Turkish fleet in the harbor under the defence of the on-shore fortifications strengthened by cannons.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Six Russian warships from Sevastopol under command of Vice Admiral Fyodor Novosilsky (including three 120-cannon first-rate ships of the line) joined Nakhimov on 28 November.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Admiral Nakhimov, was under orders from Alexander Sergeyevich Menshikov to destroy any Turkish ships carrying supplies to the Caucasus.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] His squadron included six modern battleships, two frigates, and three streamers, with the heavier Paixhans guns armed with explosive shells, their first use in a sea battle.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The Ottoman forces included seven frigates, three corvettes and two armed steamers.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The Russians planned to deploy their ships in two columns that would advance to within close range of the enemy vessels before dropping anchor and opening fire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Under Nakhimov's command, the 84-gun ship *Imperatritsa Maria* was the first to engage when she fired on the 44-gun Ottoman flagship *Auni Allah*.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] On 30 November the Russian squadron entered the harbor from the northwest in a triangular formation.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Nakhimov maneuvered his fleet so that the Ottoman vessels were between the Russian ships and Sinop's harbor defenses, shielding his own force and exposing the Ottomans to potential friendly fire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Nakhimov spaced his battleships evenly in two lines, covering the entire harbor with interlocking fields of fire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Russian gunners began to score hits on all the Ottoman targets.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The projectile shells fired for the first time from Russian guns immediately set the wooden Ottoman ships on fire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Panic-stricken sailors found firefighting efforts difficult amidst continued fire and almost constant shrapnel.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] After about 30 minutes of combat the Ottoman flag frigate *Auni Allah* was shot full of holes and ran aground when her anchor cable was cut.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] *Imperatritsa Maria* then attacked and disabled the 44-gun frigate *Fazli Allah*, which caught fire.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Meanwhile, the other Russian ships damaged the *Nizamie* and *Damiad*.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The Ottoman corvette *Guli Sephid* and frigate *Navek Bakhri* exploded.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Only one Ottoman vessel, the 12-gun paddle frigate *Taif*, managed to escape the battle while all the others were either sunk or purposely run ashore to prevent sinking.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] She fled to Istanbul and arrived on 2 December, informing the Ottoman government and Admiral Stratford of the Royal Navy of the defeat at Sinop.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Once the enemy fleet was destroyed the Russians engaged Ottoman shore batteries and destroyed them.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] During the fighting 37 Russians were killed and 229 were wounded, and at least three of the ships of the line were damaged.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Ottoman casualties included 2700 sailors killed of the 4200 present, while Sinop endured six days of bombardment.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] When telegraph reports of the battle reached Russian authorities in St.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The untested and widely hated Russian navy had proven victorious and the recent expenditure in its development seemed warranted.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Several balls were held to celebrate the victory and a state-funded parade was held.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The affair was rather grand, and included dancers, bands, parading troops who had not taken part in the battle and criminals dressed up in Ottoman uniforms.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Military advisors saw the battle as a turning point and pushed for shell-firing guns to be installed on all Russian ships.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The reaction in the Ottoman capital of Constantinople ranged from concern to total panic.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Russia had annihilated a vital convoy and now had operational control over the Black Sea.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The destruction of the harbor defenses opened the door to Russian invasion and suddenly the entire Samsun and Trabzon Coast was now at risk.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Moreover, the Russian violation of the British/French mandate for the war meant that the actions of Russia could no longer be predicted and Russia might not be fighting with one hand tied behind its back.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The attack was treated by external powers as unjustified and caused a wave of anti-Russian sentiment in western Europe.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Much of the British press presented the attack as the "Massacre of Sinope".
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The attack strengthened the pro-war factions in Britain and France, and provided them with the justification for a war to curb Russian bellicosity.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Lord Palmerston temporarily resigned over the affair.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] By March 1854, however, war hawks in the National Government won out and Sinop was seen as a just cause for war, although ultimately the real motivation was to curb Russian expansion in accordance with a balance of power strategy.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] "Turkey must be defended from aggression....
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Sinop was presented by the media as not so much a battle but an ambush, but its results were nonetheless important to the practice of 19th-century warfare and the evolution of naval doctrine.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Prior to Sinop the standard naval armament was the smooth-bore that fired cannonballs, shot, shrapnel, and other projectiles.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Paixhans guns or regional equivalents were slowly being integrated into navies, but only the French, Russian and American navies had made a comprehensive effort.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] These batteries represented a clear evolution in naval technology that broke through the final ceiling of the Age of Sail.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Unlike previous smooth-bore ordnance, Paixhans guns fired explosive shells and not mere metal projectiles.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The shells themselves did both kinetic and explosive damage, causing fires.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] In addition, the new guns were heavier, could engage at a greater range, and possessed far greater penetrating power.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] However, until 1853 no navy had made comprehensive use of shell-firing guns in a live combat environment.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] Indeed, many experts disparaged the new weapons and the larger ships required to carry them as too heavy for naval warfare.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] The results of Sinop were clear and showed that the new weapons were effective.
[src:battle-of-sinop/battle-of-sinop] As a result, an arms race ensued with participant nations desperately looking for ways to up-gun existing ships and incorporate the shell-firing guns into new ironclad vessels.
